ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELLING ON INTERSTATE 95 NORTHBOUND BY EXIT 2 IN GREENWICH, CONNECTICUT, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND GREENWICH FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE AND IMPACTED CATCH BASIN. CONNECTICUT TANK REMOVAL, INC. OF BRIDGEPORT, CONNECTICUT WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  CONNECTICUT TANK REMOVAL, INC. CONTAINED THE FREE LIQUID WITH  THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SPEEDY DRY TO THE FREE LIQUID.  TWO (2) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF SPEEDY DRY, ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND PPE WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP.  DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED BY CONNECTICUT TANK REMOVAL, INC. PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REQUIREMENTS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO 40 BOULEVARD RD, SUMTER S.C. UPON ARRIVAL AT THIS LOCATION HE NOTICED THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING ON THE TRAILER. THE FREEHOLD CARTHAGE PEOPLE CLEANED UP THE LEAK ON THERE PROPERTY.  THEN THE DRIVER WENT TO THE SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICAL FACILITY AND THEY OVERPACKED THE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING.  AFTER THEY INSPECTED THE DRUM IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM HAD A PIN HOLE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SEAM.

THE VEHICLE WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-5 WHEN THE DRIVER HAD A STEER TIRE BLOW OUT WHICH CAUSED A TRACTOR FIRE.  THIS LED TO TRAILER FIRE THAT BURNED TRACTOR/TRL AND HAD ALL CONTENTS.  I-5 NORTHBOUND AND SOUTHBOUND LANES WERE SHUT DOWN FOR APPROX. 8 HOURS.  CHEMTREC AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE CONTACTED.

DURING DELIVERY, THE DOCK PERSONNEL NOTED AN ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  CLOSER INSPECTION FOUND FREE  LIQUID ON TWO DRUMS.  THE DOCK PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE AGREED TO WEAR PPE AND ABSORB ANY FREE LIQUIDS.  TWO BUNGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE WORKED LOOSE AND LEAKED TO THE DRUM TOP.  THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE STREAM. EIGHTEEN DRUMS WERE ACCEPTED AND TWO DRUMS WERE REFUSED DUE TO THE POTENTIAL OF CONTAMINATION OF THE PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AS TO THE LOOSE BUNGS BY THE TRANSPORTER.

column168: RAILROAD EMPLOYEES OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX90687 AS IT PASSED BY IN THE BENNING YARD.  EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE TRAIN DISPATCHER, WHO IN TURN DIRECTED TRAIN Q41507 TO STOP. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ONCE THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM APPROACHED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE OUTLET PLUG FOR THE 2" AUXILIARY VALVE WAS OUT AND THE VALVE HANDLE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION (20% OPEN).  PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT THE RATE OF 16-32 OUNCES PER MINUTE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM REPLACED THE OUTLET PLUG AND CLOSED THE VALVE HANDLE.  THIS ABATED THE LEAK AND PRODUCT CEASED TO DRIP.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF THE INTERNAL TANK VALVE (TOBOV) FOUND THAT THE VALVE ROD TOOK 1/4-1/2 TURNS TO FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE.  THE PACKING NUT ON THE STUFFING BOX HAD TO BE TURNED 1-1/2 TURNS TO FULLY TIGHTEN THE PACKING NUT WITH A WRENCH.  THE AREA BELOW THE LEAKING VALVE WAS WET WITH PRODUCT.  THE IMPACTED RAIL BALLAST WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED BACK TO THE BENNING YARD (1 MILE AWAY) AND RE-INSPECTED TO ENSURE ALL VALVES AND FITTING WERE CLOSED AND SECURE.  THE INSPECTION FOUND ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS SECURE, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: CAN'T TELL REALLY HOW IT HAPPENED.  LOOKS LIKE WHILE LOADING WITH A BARREL MOVER, RUBBED UP AGAINST THE RING ON THE DRUM CAUSING TO DENT AND PUT SMALL HOLE IN DRUM DURING LOADING.

DRIVER WAS WITH CARGO TANK AND STORAGE TANK WAS IN BUILDING, OUT OF HIS SIGHT.  AS THE CARGO TANK EMPTIED, THE STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED.  DRIVER SHUT OFF ALL VALVES BUT CARGO TANK WAS EMPTY.  EITHER TOO MUCH PRODUCT WAS SHIPPED AND/OR ORDERED BY  THE CONSIGNEE.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.

IT APPEARS THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY HUMAN FAILURE.  IT LOOKS LIKE THE SHIPPER DIDN'T SECURE THE VALVES PROPERLY CAUSING SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO BE LEAKED OUT AND THUS LEAVING A RESIDUE ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  VALVE WAS CLOSED, RESIDUE SCRAPED OFF & WASHED OFF LIQUID COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE LOCATION IN THE YARD WOULD BE CALLED THE WEST WYE AND MILE POST KCS #5.

ACFX 94908, LOAD HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE. WAS IN A TRAIN DEPARTING CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GOULDING YARD, IN PENSACOLA, FL WHEN THE CREW ON A PASSING TRAIN REPORTED THE CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP. THE TRAIN MASTER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A WHITE FOAMY STREAK DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK. THE CAR WAS CUT OUT AND ISOLATED IN THE YARD. THE SHIPPER, SOLUTIA INC WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CONSIGNEE AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO REPAIR THE LEAK. THEY REPORTED THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE HAD LEAKED WHERE THE PIPE IS ATTACHED TO THE BASE PLATE. THEY TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE PIPE FLANGE AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING AND INSPECTION OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE.

THERE WAS NO MALFUNCTION OR UNCONTROLLED RELEASE, THE RELIEF VALVE ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE AND WORKED ACCORDING TO DESIGN. ALL PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY TO SOUTHEAST CHEMICAL IN SUMTER, S.C.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY HE NOTICED THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AT THE FACILITY AND THEY REMOVED THE DRUM FROM THE TRAILER AND OVERPACKED IT.  THE FACILITY ALSO CLEANED UP ANY MATERIAL THAT SPILLED OUT.  AFTER INSPECTING THE DRUM IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM HAD A PIN HOLE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SEAM.

column168: PENRECO SOLVENT (C145)LOAD/CLEVELAND TRANSFLO / 08-11-2003 AFTER THE LOAD WAS DONE. AND THE RAILCAR VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE DRIVER CLEARED HIS HOSE FROM THE PUMP TO THE TRAILER. WHEN THEY WENT TO CLEAR THE HOSE FROM THE PUMP TO THE RAILCAR, THERE WAS A MIS-COMMUNICATION BETWEEN THE DRIVER AND OUR TRANSLOADER THAT THE RAILCAR VALVE HAD ALREADY BEEN OPENED. THE DRIVER REVERSED HIS PUMP BEFORE THE TRANSLOADER COULD THROW OPEN THE RAILCAR VALVE. THE TRUCKERS'S HOSE CAME APART AT THE METAL BANDING, ALLOWING 2 GALLONS OF SOLVENT TO SPRAY ONTO THE PAVEMENT. USED FLOOR DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS TO CONTAIN AND CLEANUP SPILL. WE WILL REVIEW LOADING PROCEDURES AND CREATE A SERIES OF STEPS TO FOLLOW FOR COMMUNICATING BETWEEN LOADERS AND DRIVERS WHEN CLEARING HOSES.

column168: MOTORIST NOTIFIED OUR DRIVER OF POSSIBLE LEAK FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER CHECKED AND THERE WAS PRODUCT LEAKING AROUND THE DOME GASKET AREA INTO THE CRASH BOX. PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE PAVEMENT THROUGH THE DRAIN TUBES FROM THE CRASH BOX. FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY ARRIVED AND APPLIED SORB-ALL TO THE SMALL SPILL. THE SHIPPER ARRIVED AND HELPED TIGHTEN THE DOME LID. THE TRAILER WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FACILITY WHERE A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED. THE SHIPPER SWEPT UP THE SORB-ALL AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IT, THE ROADWAY WAS RINSED OFF BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO HIS DELIVERY POINT. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON POST LOADING PROCEDURE OF CHECKING HIS DOME AREA AND DOME LID FOR SECURITY.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN COUNTY ROAD (GRAVEL) IN STRAIGHT TRUCK W/TANK, PULLING PUP TRANKER TRAILER.  IN EFFORT TO AVOID HITTING AN ANTELOPE, DRIVER MOVED TO RIGHT SIDE OF ROAD.  TRAILER REAR WHEELS GOT TOO CLOSE TO DITCH AND BEGAN RIDING INTO DITCH.  AFTER 1/4 - 1/2 MILE TRAILER TILTED OVER AND EVENTUALLY FLIPPED CAUSING ST. TRUCK TO FLIP AS WELL.  A PORTION OF THE TANKER TRAILER BODY WAS TORN OPEN ALLOWING RELEASE.

FORKLIFT PUNCTURE WAS THE CAUSE OF DAMAGE AND RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  ALL PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

AN EMPTY RAIL FLATCAR DERAILED INTO THE SIDE OF TEIX 25077 THAT WAS STANDING ON AN ADJACENT TRACK. THE CORNER OF THE FLATCAR BED IMPACTED THE TANK SHELL APPROX. ONE FOOT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE SIDE SHELL NEAR THE EDGE OF THE TANKS B-END HEAD. THE IMPACT CAUSED A ONE-FOOT GASH IN TEIX 25077 SIDE SHELL, RELEASING PRODUCT. A TEMPORARY DIKE WAS BUILT TO CONTAIN LIQUID ASPHALT. NO WATERWAYS OR SEWERS WERE IMPACTED. THE SPILLED ASPHALT WAS SCRAPED-UP DURING SOLIDIFICATION & TAKEN TO AN APPROVED LANDFILL.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A REFINED FUEL TANKER AT A BULK PLANT FACILITY. HE CHECKED THE GAUGE TO THE TANK & NOTICE IT WAS RISING, SO PRODUCT WAS GOING INTO THE STORAGE TANK. HE WENT BACK TO THE TANKER & WAS DOING A WALK AROUND INSPECTION WHEN PRODUCT STARTED SPILLING OUT OF ANOTHER TANK. OUR DRIVER DID NOT REALIZE THAT A VALVE WAS OPEN TO A SMALLER SECOND TANK & PRODUCT WAS BEING PUMPED INTO THIS TANK ALSO, DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CLOSE ALL VALVES. ALL PRODUCT WAS HELD IN CONTAINMENT AREA. THE FREE STANDING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT AND A SPILL KIT AND FLOOR DRY WERE USED TO CLEAN UP THE REMAINING PRODUCT. CONTENTS WERE PUT INTO CONTAINERS & DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

THE DRIVER'S INJURY WAS VERY MINOR, HE WAS NEVER WRITTEN OFF WORK AND THE BURNS WERE SO MINOR THEY COULD NOT BE CLASSIFIED.

column168: ON 8/5/03 AT 0340 AM, PAM TRANSPORT DRIVER CONTACTED CENTRAL DISPATCH, ADVISING OF A LEAK ATTRIBUTED TO A POSSIBLE LOAD SHIFT. THE FOLLOWING SEQUENCE OF EVENTS (SOE) ARE PROVIDED: 8/4/03/1900 BUMPED DOCK 4, ECOLAB, MCDONOUGH, GA - 8/4/03/2100 - BEGAN LOADING (LOADING DIAGRAM ATTACHED) 8/4/03/2345 LOADING COMPLETED DRIVER WENT ACROSS STREET TO SCALE, SCALE CLOSED. PARKED IN THE AREA DUE TO I75 REPAVING ONGOING. 8/5/03/0230 REPAVING COMPLETED, PROCEEDED NORTH ON I75 TO WEST I285 THEN NORTH ON I285. AT MILE MARKER 5, A DARK COLORED VEHICLE, PARKED ON SHOULDER, SUDDENLY PULLED OUT ONTO THE RIGHT LANE W/ NO SIGNALS. THE TWO LANES TO THE LEFT WERE OCCUPIED. HENCE, PAM DRIVER SLOWED RAPIDLY TO AVOID CONTACT. THEN, PROCEEDED TO I85 WEST, FULTON IND BLVD, ATLANTA, GA TO SCALE AT A QUIK TRIP (QT)/"CAT SCALE". 8/5/03/0315-0445 PAM DRIVER SCALED, SET TRAILER TANDEMS, CONDUCTED TIRE CHECKS. DURING WALK AROUND INSPECTION, NOTICED WETNESS ON OUT SIDE OF TRAILER. DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH FOR INSTRUCTIONS/MOVED UNIT TO SAFE AREA. AFTER ASSESSING SITUATION AND TO STEM ANY SEEPAGE WITHIN THE TRAILER, DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PURCHASE AND SPREAD FLOOR DRY AND RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. 8/5/03/0545 PAM DRIVER RETURNED/ REDOCKED FOR SHIPPER LOAD INSPECTION.  LOAD WAS CHECKED/CONFIRMED THAT A SHIFT HAD OCCURRED. EVIDENTLY A PORTION OF A 55 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER MOVED OFF ITS PALLET. A PUNCTURE WAS DISCOVERED ABOUT THE MIDDLE PORTION OF THE PLASTIC DRUM THAT HAD MOVED OFF ITS PALLET. NO OTHER CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF LIQUID HAD SEEPED FROM THE DAMAGED/PUNCTURED PLASTIC DRUM ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. REASON AS TO WHAT CAUSED THE DRUM TO BE PUNCTURED, COULD NOT BE DETERMINED. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SUBSEQUENTLY REMOVED, WITH TRAILER CLEANUP BEING COMPLETED AT THE SHIPPER LOCATION.

A TOTE FELL OFF TRAILER AND LANDED INTO A CONCRETE DRAINAGE AREA. THE TOTE CRACKED AND RUPTURED RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF ETHANOL INTO A CONCRETE CULVERT. THE ORANGE FIRE DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED B&B FIRE & SAFETY SERVICES, INC. TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND COMPLETE ENVIRONMENT REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES. ETHANOL THAT WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONCRETE CULVERT WAS PUMPED OUT WITH A VACUUM TRUCK. THE CONCRETE DRAIN AND CULVERT WERE WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND PUMPED OUT WITH THE VACUUM TRUCK IN ORDER TO REMOVE ALL ETHANOL CONTAINED IN THESE AREAS. ALL WASTE WAS CONTAINERIZED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL AND THE SITE WAS RESTORED BACK TO ORIGINAL CONDITIONS.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: SHIPMENT ORIGINATED IN CDG THROUGH DFW TO LAX. TWO BOXES CONTAINING A TOTAL OF 24 FLAMMABLE AEROSOL PRODUCTS IDENTIFIED AS NEGEROL AEROSOL WERE DISCOVERED AT LAX CARGO. ULD CONTAINER WITH SHIPMENT WAS BEING UNLOADED AT LAX CARGO TO PREPARE FOR DELIVERY AIR TAHITI. WHILE BEING REMOVED FROM CONTAINER A BOX FELL ONTO THE GROUND EXPOSING INNER BOX THAT CONTAINED FLAMMABLE PLACARD. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE AEROSOL CAN WAS PUNCTURED. SPILL WAS MINIMAL AND CONTAINED WITHIN THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX. ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS SUSPENDED AND PLACED IN DG HOLDING AREA WHILE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND COMPLETED THEIR INVESTIGATION OF THE CONTENTS. AMERICAN AIRLINES CONDUCTS YEARLY TRAINING ON HAZ AND DG'S AND EMPLOYEES ARE TRAINED TO IDENTIFY AND RESPOND TO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENTS. ALTHOUGH IT IS A KNOWN SHIPPER'S OBLIGATION TO REPORT DANGEROUS GOODS IN SHIPMENTS, AGENTS ARE TRAINED TO ASK QUESTIONS AND LOOK FOR TRIGGERS THAT MAY INDICATE HIDDEN DG'S. CARGO WILL NOTIFY SHIPPER AND EDUCATE ON RESPONSIBILITIES WHEN TRANSPORTING SHIPMENTS.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A DELIVERY OF FIVE TOTES OF BLEACH TO THE STRUTHERS WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT IN STRUTHERS, OHIO.  ONE THE THEIR EMPLOYEES WAS OFFLOADING THE TOTES WITH THE USE OF A FORKLIFT AND THE LEFT FORK ON THE LIFT STRUCK THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TOTE, BREAKING IT OFF AND CAUSING THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE (330 GALS OF BLEACH)  TO BE RELEASED OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WENT INTO THE PLANT'S EFFLUENT SYSTEM AND WAS TREATED RESULTING IN NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT.
UPON ARRIVAL AT A TRANSFER FACILITY ONE BATTERY WAS CRACKED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT.  THE DAMAGED BATTERY WAS SEALED SHUT AND PLACED IN OS&D TO AWAIT DISPOSITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, A YELLOW POWDER WAS NOTICED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  APPROXIMATELY TWO CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE CARDBOARD CARTON BEING PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENT PADS, AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THREE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. EMPLOYEES INHALED THE FREE PRODUCT AND COMPLAINED OF IRRITATION TO NASAL PASSAGES.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, WERE EXAMINED AND LATER RELEASED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, FOUR WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE JUGS BEING DAMAGED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GLOVES, BOOTIES AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FOUR WET CARTONS AND TWO DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE FOURTEEN UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO FIVE, FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS.  ALL FIVE DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DEFECTIVE VAPOR VALVE EDCX 6036 AUGUST 18 2003 SOUTHEAST DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0500 HOURS, MONDAY AUGUST 18, 2003, AT PAVONIA YARD CAMDEN NJ A CONRAIL CREW NOTED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM TANK CAR EDCX 6036 LOAD NITRIC ACID CLASS 8 UN 2031 PG I AROUND PROTECTIVE HOUSING. A CAR SHIFTED OUT ALONG WITH 3-4 CARS ON EITHER END, OF TRAIN TO ISOLATE TEMPORARILY ON THE WEST END OF THE CLASS YARD'S LADDER TRACK BY THE ENGINE HOUSE. INSPECTION BY CONTRACTOR REACT AND CR RISK MANAGEMENT NOTED VAPOR LEAK ORIGINATING FROM VAPOR VALVE. INSIDE OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING, INCLUDING ALL VALVES, NOTED WITH PRODUCT RESIDUE. CAR MOVED AND ISOLATED ON BUD TRACK. PRESSURE GAUGE APPLIED TO THE VAPOR VALVE CLOSURE PLUG ORIFICE NOTED "6 PSI" FURTHER INSPECTION OF VAPOR VALVE NOTED THE VAPOR VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE APPEARED SLIGHTLY MISALIGNED. ATTEMPTS TO RESEAT VALVE PROPERLY FAILED TO TOTALLY SECURE VAPOR RELEASE. VAPOR PRESSURE BLED DOWN/ SCRUBBED T "0 PSI" THRU 55 GALLON POLY DRUM OF CAUSTIC SOLUTION. EACH SECTION OF THE VAPOR VALVE WAS EXAMINED AS TI WAS REMOVED. THE GASKET OF THE VAPOR VALVE FLANGE ASSEMBLY APPEARED MISALIGNED. ADDITIONALLY THE TOP SIDE OF THE VAPOR VALVE FLANGE NOTED THE WELDING PROCESS FOR ATTACHING THE 1" NOZZLE TO THE FLANGE ALLOWED AN UNDERCUTTING INTO THE FLANGE ASSEMBLY NEGATING A PROPER SEAL OF VAPOR/PRODUCT FOR TRANSPORTATION. CONTRACTOR HMHTTC REBUILT THE VAPOR VALVE WITH TRIM (STAINLESS STEEL) WHICH WAS REAPPLIED TO THE CAR REACT. NO FURTHER LEAKS DETECTED. CAR OKAY FOR MOVEMENT TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE. ADDITIONAL NOTES: TANK CAR IS DOT-SPECIFICATION 111A6ALW2 AND EQUIPPED WITH A "75" PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE 6" BLIND FLANGE LOCATED INSIDE THE "A" END OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS NOTED WITH TWO OF EIGHT SECUREMENT NUTS "SHORT" (STUD NOT COMPLETELY ENGAGING THE NUT) SECUREMENT PLUG FOR THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (REQUIRING ONE HALF TURN FOR TOTAL SECUREMENT) TWO OF FOUR VAPOR VALVE FLANGE SECUREMENT NUTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (REQUIRING ONE-QUARTER TO ONE-HALF TURN ON EACH FOR TOTAL SECUREMENT). MINOR DRIPPING OF PRODUCT THRU DRAIN PIPES AFFIXED EACH SIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND DOWN ALONGSIDE THE CAR WAS REMEDIATED AND REMOVED BY REACT. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM REACT (AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR) ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED, AND THE SECUREMENT PLUG FOR VALVE NOT TOOL TIGHT. VALVE WAS CLOSED AND SECUREMENT PLUG TIGHTENED. TANK CAR SECURED AND OKAYED FOR DESTINATION. CAUSE CODE 379 DEFECTIVE VAPOR VALVE NARRI = 5(5+7+0) X (2+0)=120

PERSONNEL, FOUR (4) CARTONS CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED WET INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE FOUR (4) CONTAMINATED CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO TWO (2) 95-GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  BOTH OVERPACK DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION. ON 9/8/03 DRIVER FOR CTL DISTRIBUTION ARRIVED AT SIEGAL ROBERTS ELEC. PLATE IN RIPLEY TO DELIVER A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO TAKE A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED AND PRESENT THE SAMPLE TO THE PLANT OPERATOR. AFTER THE SAMPLE WAS TAKEN THE DRIVER STARTED TO MAKE THE NECESSARY CONNECTION TO THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK. THE DRIVER MADE ALL OF THE NECESSARY CONNECTIONS AND WAS WAITING FOR THE SAMPLE TO BE APPROVED. THE APPROVAL WAS GIVEN AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO START THE UNLOADING PROCESS. AS THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK AND PLACED A 5-GALLON BUCKET UNDER THE CONNECTION THAT WAS LEAKING. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO BLEED THE PRODUCT OFF THE LINES AND MAKE THE CORRECTIONS NEEDED TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING. THE DRIVER REPLACED THE HOSE GASKET AND THAN PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE DISCHARGE VALVES OF THE CARGO TANK. AS THE DRIVER OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE IT APPEARED THAT THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE DRIVER OPENED THE CUSTOMER'S LINE AND STARTED TO AIR-UP THE CARGO TANK TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT. AS THE AIR STARTED TO BUILD THE CONNECTION STARTED TO LEAK. THE DRIVERS IMMEDIATELTY CLOSED THE DISCHARGE LINE VALVE AN BLED THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE UNLOADING LINE. AS THE DRIVER STARTED TO DISCONNECT THE UNLOADING LINE THERE WAS A POCKET OF AIR IN THE LINE THAT DRIVER FAILED TO ACKNOWLEDGE AND THE PRESSURE FORCED PRODUCT FROM THE UNLOADING LINE. THE DRIVER WAS SPLASHED WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE LEFT SIDE OF HIS FACE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STARTED RINSING HIS FACE UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL IN RIPLEY, TN TO BE EVALUATED. THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL WITHIN 2 HOURS. PLANT PERSONNEL FROM THEIR WASTEWATER FACILITY CONTAINED THE SPILL AND NEUTRALIZED THE 25 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WITH LIME. THEIR WASTEWATER FACILITY PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT. THE LOADED CARGO TANK WAS REDELIVERED THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER SPILL PREVENTION AND AWARENESS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS, 8-27-03, TONY ENSLEY, AN APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE, DISCOVERED OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE SIDE DOOR ON UNIT #21206, A 2001 ISUZU FRR BOX TRUCK, PARKED IN THE WAREHOUSE PARKING LOT AT THE DUNCAN BRANCH. THE VEHICLE WAS FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. ENSLEY RETRIEVED THE KEYS FROM DISPATCH AND RETURNED TO THE TRUCK AND OPENED THE SIDE DOOR, THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK. THERE WAS ICE AND CONDENSATION AROUND THE VALVES AND UNDERNEATH THE TRUCK MOUNTED HL 190, CRYOGENIC CARGO TANK. HE IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE AREA AROUND THE TRUCK FROM VEHICLE AND PEDESTRIAN TRAFFIC. AT APPROXIMATELY 0810 HOURS, 8-27-03, SHERIE HARMON, BRANCH MANAGER, ARRIVED AT THE OFFICE. SHE WAS IMMEDIATELY ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND SHE CONTACTED THE DUNCAN FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND TAPED OFF THE AREA TO ALLOW FOR THE SAFE EVAPORATION OF THE LEAKING OXYGEN. FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS DEPARTMENT. TONY BARNETT, ASSISTANT DIRECTOR OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ADMINISTRATION RESPONDED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HOURS, 8-27-03, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MR. BARNETT DETERMINED THAT THE SITUATION WAS SAFE AND LEFT THE FACILITY. AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, 8-27-03, AFTER THE ICE HAD COMPLETELY MELTED THE TANK WAS INSPECTED BY TRAVIS PARKER, LOGISTICS SUPERVISOR. ALL COMPONENTS WERE FOUND TO BE FUNCTIONING PROPERLY. THE SECONDARY FILL VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE SLIGHTLY OPEN, BUT WAS FOUND TO FUNCTION PROPERLY. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT AN UNSECURED DOLLY HAD BEEN FOUND SITTING ADJACENT TO THE VALVE. AS TRUCK HAD BEEN SECURED SINCE IT WAS LAST OPERATED, IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE UNSECURED DOLLY MAY HAVE MADE CONTACT WITH THE VALVE DURING TRANSPORT, CAUSING THE VALVE TO BE PARTIALLY OPENED RESULTING IN A SLOW RELEASE OF THE OXYGEN. THE DRIVER WHO PARKED THE TRUCK WAS, THOMAS LAWSON, AN APRIA HEALTHCARE CLINICAL SERVICE TECHNICIAN. LAWSON IS A 5+ YEAR EMPLOYEE WITH A CLASS B CDL WITH HAZMAT AND TANK ENDORSEMENTS. HE RECEIVED HIS LAST HAZMAT TRAINING VERIFICATION ON 3-6-01. LAWSON ADVISED THAT AFTER HE PARKED THE TRUCK ON 8-26-03 HE HAD CHECKED THE DOOR TO VERIFY THAT IT WAS LOCKED. AT THAT TIME THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF ANY LEAK. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. CORRECTIVE ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN WITH DRIVER LAWSON.

column168: THE DRIVER RECEIVED INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE RECEIVING SUPERVISOR AS WERE TO HOOK-UP THE DISCHARGE HOSE. THE SUPERVISOR UNLOCKED THE GATE FOR THE DRIVER TO BACK INTO THE UNLOADING AREA. THE SUPERVISOR SAID IT WAS OKAY TO AIR UNLOAD. THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK AND PRODUCT STARTED FLOWING INTO THE STORAGE TANK AND A CHEMICAL REACTION TOOK PLACE. DRIVER SHUT OFF VALVE AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR--ALL WORKERS EXITED THE AREA. REGION 6 EPA AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED INCIDENT #653715. CONSIGNEE TOOK CHARGE OF INCIDENT. LA STATE POLICE HAZMAT DIVISION WAS ALSO ON SITE. RAPIDS PARISH BOARD OF HEALTH. PETRON HAZMAT CONTRACTORS CLEANED UP.

column168: CSXT FREIGHT TRAIN Q626-27 DERAILED AT MP-QC 349.9 ON AUGUST 28, 2003 AT 11:45 HOURS, IN THE STATE OF NEW YORK, COUNTY OF WAYNE, TOWNSHIP OF PALMYRA.  14 OF THE 90 CARS IN THE TRAIN CONSIST DERAILED, 60TH THROUGH THE 73RD CAR FROM THE HEADEND.  THE 14 CARS CONTAINED RESIDUE LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS (PROPANE) UN1075.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE WAYNE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGER DEPARTMENT EVACUATED 5 HOMES AND 3 BUSINESSES THAT WERE ADJACENT TO THE DERAILMENT SITE, UNTIL THE DERAILED RESIDUE LPG CARS WERE INSPECTED FOR INTEGRITY AND SECUREMENT.  A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL REPRESENTATIVE CONDUCTED THIS INSPECTION.  THE EVACUATION LASTED APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS AND 50 MINUTES, AND THEN ALL RESIDENTS AND BUSINESSES WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN THEIR RESPECTIVE PROPERTIES.  ALL OF THE DERAILED RESIDUE LPG CARS WERE CLEANED AND PURGED ON SITE BY CSXT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS.

THE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER, KOPPERS INDUSTRIES, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE TOP-OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN 1/4 TURN AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION BELL CAP WAS LOOSE 1/4 TURN.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE BELL CAP WAS MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  THEY ARE INVESTIGATING.

THE CAR WAS INSPECTED ON 9-1-03 BY THE CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE PROTECTIVE COVER OF THE VALVE STAND WAS OPEN AND THE CAP FOR THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WAS MISSING.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD COLLECTED IN THE PROTECTIVE COVER LID.  THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE DID NOT HAVE A VALVE, BUT RATHER A 3" QUICK CONNECT MALE FITTING.  AS THIS WAS A BONDED LOAD OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE (WHISKEY) IT IS ASSUMED THAT VANDALS OPENED THE PROTECTIVE COVER LID AND REMOVED THE CAP FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  A NEW CAP WAS OBTAINED AND INSTALLED ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND CLOSURES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SEALED AND IN GOOD CONDITION. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CSXT POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO INVESTIGATE THE POSSIBLE VANDALISM OR THEFT OF THE LADING.

column168: ON AUGUST 25, 2003, AN ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC., VAN LEFT THE ACI WAREHOUSE IN MARYLAND HEIGHTS, MO ENROUTE TO THE LAMBERT INTERLATIONAL ST. LOUIS AIRPORT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 AM, THE TRUCK WAS NORTHBOUND ON LINDBERG BLVD APPROACHING THE AIRPORT EXIT WHEN THE REAR DOOR CAME OPEN.  A MOTORIST SAW THE OPEN DOOR AND ALERTED THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD, DID NOT FIND ANYTHING AMISS AND CONTINUED ON TO THE AIRPORT.  HE DELIVERED HIS PACKAGES AND RETURNED TO THE WAREHOUSE.  ON THE RETURN TRIP HE NOTICED A PACKAGE WITH A RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS LABEL ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY.  THE BOX HAD BEEN RUN OVER BY ONE OR MORE VEHICLES WHICH CAUSED SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE CONTENTS.  RESPONDING TO THE EVENT WERE THE BRIDGETON POLICE, THE MALLINCKRODT RESPONSE TEAM AND ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC., PERSONNEL.  THE POLICE BLOCKED THE LANE IN WHICH THE SPILL OCCURRED.  MALLINCKRODT PERSONNEL SURVEYED THE ROADWAY AND RECOVERED INTACT 3 OF THE 8 DIAGNOSTIC CAPSULES INVOLVED.  THEY REMOVED THE 8 HALF CAPSULES AND PACKAGING MATERIALS FROM THE ROADWAY AND SWEPT UP THE AREA.  RADIOACTIVE WASTE AND DEBRIS WERE RETAINED BY MALLINCKRODT PERSONNEL.  RECOVERY TOOK ABOUT 45 MINUTES.  THE DRIVER WAS PLACED ON SUSPENSION UNTIL HE COMPLETED RETRAINING AND DRUG TESTING.

ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column168: THE PURPOSE OF THIS ADDENDUM REPORT IS TO DOCUMENT THE EVENTS OF A CRASH THAT OCCURRED ON 08/25/03 ON I-72 WESTBOUND AT MILEPOST 41.9.  THE IDOT CONTROL NUMBER IS 7849043.  THE DISTRICT 20 CRASH REPORT NUMBER IS 20-03-532, AND THE INCIDENT NUMBER IS I#15839.  UNIT 1 WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I-72 APPROXIMATELY 0.1 MILES WEST OF MILEPOST 42, WHICH IS LOCATED ON THE TWIN EAGLE BRIDGES WHEN IT APPROACHED TWO OTHER UNITS ON THE BRIDGE THAT WERE BEGINNING TO SET UP THE CONSTRUCTION ZONES ON THE BRIDGE. UNIT 2 WAS ALSO WESTBOUND IN THE DRIVING LINE AND WAS SLOWING DOWN TO PULL OFF ONTO THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF THE BRIDGE.  UNIT 3 WAS PARKED ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE SHOULDER OF THE BRIDGE AND THE DRIVER OF UNIT 3 HAD ALREADY EXITED THE VEHICLE AND WAS WALKING ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER OF UNIT 1 ADVISED HE DID NOT SEE THE UNIT 2 IN FRONT OF HIM UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE.  UNIT 1 THEN SLAMMED ON THE BRAKES AND BEGAN SKIDDING.  UNIT 1 REAR ENDED THE TRAILER BEING PULLED BY UNIT 2 WHICH CAUSED UNIT 2 TO BREAK AWAY FROM ITS TRAILER AND OVERTURN ONTO ITS SIDE.  UNIT 1 THEN SIDESWIPED UNIT 3 WHICH WAS PARKED ON THE SHOULDER AND THEN HIT THE DRIVER OF UNIT 3, WHOM WAS A PEDESTRIAN ON THE BRIDGE.  UNIT 1 THEN SWERVED AND HIT THE SIDE OF THE BRIDGE ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER WHERE IT CAME TO REST AND CAUGHT ON FIRE.  UNIT 2 CAME TO REST IN THE PASSING LANE ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE AND ALSO CAUGHT ON FIRE.  UNIT 3 REMAINED PARKED ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER AND THE DRIVER OF UNIT 3 WAS LOCATED ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER AFTER HE WAS STRUCK BY UNIT 1.

WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 80 TRANSMISSION IN TRUCK LITERALLY "BLEW UP" HEATED & SMOLDERING PARTS SENT IN EVERY DIRECTION PASSENGER SIDE OF UNIT ENGULFED IN FLAMES. DRIVER PULLED UNIT OFF ROADWAY ONTO SHOULDER. FLYING PIECES FROM TRANSMISSION CAUSED DAMAGED TO FUEL TANK ON REEFER TRAILER. TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE ENTIRE UNIT BURNED UP WITH PRODUCT INSIDE TRAILER. COPIES OF DETAILED INFORMATION ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. ALL INFORMATION WAS JUST RECENTLY RECEIVED ENABLING US TO FINALLY FILE THIS REPORT.

THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT EXTENDED APPROXIMATELY 2 INCHES BEYOND THE TOTE.  UPON PLACING THE TOTE ONTO THE VAN, ONE OF THE BLADES STRUCK A 55-GALLON DRUM CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS KEVIN GAREN GARY GRAGG, WILLIAM HENDERSON AND THOMAS CASPER DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 1 X1 GALLON METAL CAN OF "BONDO BODY FILLER" THE LABEL ON THIS METAL CAN STATED "FLAMMABLE." THIS METAL CAN HAD A FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE THAT WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THIS CLOSURE CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE CAN TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF ONE GALLON. THIS SHIPMENT ALSO CONTAINED SEVERAL OTHER NON REGULATED WOOD WORKING MATERIALS, TOOLS AND SUPPLIES. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THERE WERE SIX EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. CLEAR OF SCENE 0008 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON OHIO.

OF THE REMAINING 11 BOXES, 7 OF THEM CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING ITEMS THAT DID NOT LEAK: 3 X 3.785 OF "PRO POWER ACID CLEANER" (PACKAGED SAME AS ABOVE), 2 X 3.785 L OF "SLAM" IN PLASTIC BOTTLES  WITH SCREW CLOSURES NOT SECURED  BY POSITIVE MEANS MARKED "CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (CONTAIN SODIUM HYDROXIDE, 2-BUTOXYETHANOL), 6, UN 1760, PG II", 2 X 32 OZ OF "LA CERA AMARILLA" IN PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS MARKED "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (CONTAINS PETROLEUM DISTILLATES), 3, UN 1993, PG II" 2 X 13 OZ OF" ARO-472 PRO SHINE IN METAL AEROSOL SPRAY CANS MARKED "EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE" AND 1 X 3.785 L OF "1600 LACQUER THINNER GENERAL PURPOSE" IN A METAL CAN WITH S SCREW TYPE CLOSURE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS MARKED "FLAMMABLE" AND "DANGER POISON". THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOXES, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENTS AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENTS IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THEM INTO RECOVERY DRUMS. THESE SHIPMENTS WERE HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID. HE IMMEDIATELY WASHED AFFECTED AREA WITH SOAP AND WATER, WAS ADVISED WHAT THE LIQUID WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. CLEAR OF SCENE 0314. THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT HE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

CIRCUMSTANCES: EMERGENCY RESPONDER DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE VERIFIED THAT PORTABLE TANK (IBC) 181340 WAS DRIPPING LIQUID AT THE BOTTOM VALVE. IBC 181340 REPRESENTED ONE OF FIVE IBCS ON BOARD VAN TRAILER 71806. UPON VISUAL INSPECTION, THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE LEAK WAS DIFFICULT TO DETECT. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY APPARENT DAMAGE. MOREOVER, ALL THE OTHER MATERIALS ON BOARD APPEARED TO BE INTACT BASED ON DELIVERY TICKET 24304130. THESE MATERIALS INCLUDED 30 AMMONIA CYLINDERS, 18 EMPTY DELDRUMS, 12 PHOSPHORIC ACID DRUMS, 1 NITRIC ACID DRUM, AND A PAINT DRUM. OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND INCIDENT COMMAND ON THE SCENE MADE THE DECISION TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO ANOTHER IBC. THE IBC WITH THE BAD VALVE WOULD BE TRANSPORTED TO OUR ST ALBANS BRANCH AND THEN RETURNED TO HENDERSON FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. CAUSE: OUR ST.ALBANS BRANCH SHIPPER IBC 181340 BACK TO THE HENDERSON FACILITY. BILL WILSON JR., ACID DEPT. SUPERVISOR, FILLED THE IBC WITH WATER AND PRESSURIZED THE TANK. HE PINPOINTED THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE LEAK AT THE TOP BACK PORTION OF THE VALVE ASSEMBLY. ON 8/28/03, BILL DISMANTLED THE VALVE. IT WAS VERY EVIDENT THAT THE GASKET HAD DETERIORATED. THEREFORE WE ATTRIBUTE THE ROOT CAUSE TO THE AGE AND FATIGUE OF THE GASKET. ANOTHER CONTRIBUTING FACTOR RELATES TO THE MULTI-PIECE CONSTRUCTION OF THE VALVE THAT IS HELD TOGETHER BY A SIX-BOLT ASSEMBLY. WE COUNTED 6 POSSIBLE PLACED WHERE THE VALVE COULD POSSIBLE DEVELOP A LEAK. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: THE IBC 181340 WILL BE FITTED WITH A NEWER STYLE VALVE THAT IS A 4-BOLT ASSEMBLY AND ONLY 2-PIECE CONSTRUCTION INCLUDING A PVC VALVE STEM THAT IS MORE CORROSION RESISTANT. OUR DISTRICT OPERATIONS MANAGER, ANDY CLEMENTS, STATED THAT EFFECTIVE 8/28/03, WE WILL REPLACE THE SIX-BOLT VALVE ASSEMBLY WITH THE NEW REPLACEMENT VALVE ON ALL IBCS AS THEY ARE BEING FILLED. DUE TO THE AGE OF THE IBCS IN SERVICE THAT THE 6-BOLT VALVE, THIS WILL SERVE TO PREVENT THE POTENTIAL FOR ANY FUTURE LEAKS OF THIS NATURE. WE HAD ALREADY IMPLEMENTED MEASURES TO REPLACE THE 6-BOLT MULTI-PIECE VALVES ON IBCS DEDICATED FOR HYDROCHLORIC ACID SERVICE WITH THE 4-BOLT VALVE 2-PIECE CONSTRUCTION. THE NEWER VALVES HAVE HELPED TO ELIMINATE PROBLEMS WITH CORROSION OF METALLIC PARTS. IN ADDITION, WE HAD ALREADY IMPLEMENTED CONTROLS FOR PURCHASING NEW IBCS FITTED WITH NEWER VALVE CONSTRUCTION AS PREVENTIVE MEASURES. SINCE IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO EXAMINE THE INTEGRITY OF THE GASKET UNLESS YOU REMOVE THE VALVE AND COMPLETELY DISMANTLE THE COMPONENTS, WE FEEL IT WILL BE MORE COST-EFFECTIVE IN LONG RUN TO REPLACE THE 6-BOLT VALVE ON ALL IBCS AS THEY ARE FILLED AS A PREVENTIVE MEASURE AND ELIMINATE THE POTENTIAL RISK OF ANOTHER GASKET FAILURE ON THE OLDER VALVES CURRENTLY IN SERVICE.
FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS WEARING REQUIRED PPE

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: ON 8/14/03, CALVIN GILBERT, A DRIVER FOR RESEARCH SOLVENTS AND CHEMICALS (RSC) DROVE THE BULK TRUCK TO DELIVER RSC PRODUCT RN-1001 THINNER TO MCWANE PIPE LOCATED IN BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA. CALVIN DELIVERED HIS FIRST LOAD OF PRODUCT TO ONE OF MCWANE'S PRODUCTION LINES WITHOUT INCIDENT. CALVIN WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO ANOTHER PRODUCTION LINE AT MCWANE PIPE WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. CALVIN WAS LOADING RN-1001 THINNER FROM THE BULK TRUCK TO A PORTABLE CONTAINER WHEN A FIRE/EXPLOSION OCCURRED. MCWANE EMPLOYEES RESPONDED BY ASSISTING CALVIN AND CLOSING OFF THE VALVE ON THE LOADING LINE. A SMALL AMOUNT OF RN1001 THINNER (LESS THAN 1 GALLON) WAS SPILLED WITHIN A CONTAINED AREA. RESCUE PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND CALVIN WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL VIA AMBULANCE FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT. CALVIN GILBERT RECEIVED 2ND DEGREE BURNS OVER 10-20% OF HIS BODY. AN INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED AND I WAS DETERMINED THAT SPLASH FILLING HAD BEEN CONDUCTED IN LOADING THE PORTABLE BULK CONTAINER AND STATIC ELECTRICITY MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT. RSC REVIEWED ITS WRITTEN PROCEDURES ADDRESS BOTH PROPER GROUNDING/BONDING AND UTILIZING SUBMERGED FILLING WHEN LOADING FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. SUBMERGED FILLING AND PROPER GROUNDING/BONDING ARE BEING UTILIZED TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THE INCIDENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: JERMAINE JOHNSON, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR ON TRACK 791 IN EL CENTRO, NEAR EUCLID AND FOURTH STREETS.  MR. JOHNSON ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SET OUT AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  DENNIS JOHNSON ADVISED MR. JOHNSON TO CONTACT THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ROBERT BAVIER, CHEMICAL MANAGER OF TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED, WITH AN ETA OF FOUR TO FIVE HOURS. MGR. BAVIER CONTACTED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE THE LEAKING TANKCAR. CHEMTREC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES DISCOVERED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS A HOLE THREE FOOT FROM THE TOP ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  A SMALL POOL OF MATERIAL WAS FOUND UNDER THE CAR. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ON SCENE STATED VAPORS WERE DETECTED WITHIN FIVE FEET OF THE TANKCAR, HOWEVER, NO EVACUATION WAS BEING CONSIDERED. MGR. BAVIER PLACED A TEMPORARY PATCH OVER THE HOLE IN THE TANK CAR. CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO AN EMPTY TANK CAR. AFTER THE TRANSFER, BOTH TANK CARS WERE DECONTAMINATED. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND THE TRACK BALLAST WAS NEUTRALIZED BY THE CONTRACTOR.

BILL LARSON, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 642074, A LOAD OF MOLTEN PHENOL, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR IN LIVONIA YARD, YARD ONE, TRACK 23, IN THE BOWL, AND CONDUCTOR KURT ANDERSON WAS EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT. DAVID JARREAU, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, WAS TRANSPORTING CONDUCTOR ANDERSON TO LADY OF THE LAKES HOSPITAL IN BATON ROUGE, LA. FRANK LERCH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED AND AND REQUESTED RMCC MAKE IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER, GEORGIA GULF CORP. VIA CHEMTREC. MSDS INFORMATION WAS ALSO REQUESTED.  THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED FROM THE BOWL TO THE HAZ MAT TRACK. TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE LIVONIA YARD. STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO DEQ AND DPS. JEFF, CTEH, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT DR. GOAD. AT 06:15 PM, MSDS WAS RECEIVED AT RMCC AND FAXED TO LADY OF THE LAKES HOSPITAL IN BATON ROUGE, LA. DOCTOR GOAD, CTEH, DISPATCHED AN AIR MONITOR TEAM TO THE LIVONIA YARD. THE SHIPPER, GEORGIA GULF CORPORATION, DISPATCHED HULCHER SERVICES, FOR CLEANUP OF THE TANKCAR. MGR. ROBINSON DISCOVERED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON TOP OF THE TANKCAR. PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND A FEW DROPS HAD REACHED THE TOP OF THE RAILS. DAVID STANTON, CLAIMS AGENT, AND ASSISTANT CHIEF DAVIDSON, LIVONIA FIRE DEPARTMENT, WERE ON SCENE WITH MGR. ROBINSON. AT 08:10 PM, MGR. FRANK LERCH ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD DISPATCHED BRETT ABEAR, COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE, TO LIVONIA YARD, AND AN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENIST TO THE HOSPITAL. HULCHER SERVICES PERSONNEL WEARING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WERE ABLE TO SECURE THE LIQUID LINE VALVE STEM PACKING RETAINER. HULCHER PERSONNEL ALSO CLEANED THE TANKCAR.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS RELEASED FROM THE SCENE. DEQ AND DPS PERSONNEL WERE ON THE SCENE, AS WELL AS, CTEH PERSONNEL WITH AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT. AT 10:37 PM, MGR. ROBINSON REPORTED THE TANKCAR WAS SECURE ND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON IN TRANSPORTATION. DAVID STANTON, CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE, ADVISED THE EMPLOYEE HAD BEEN EXAMINED AND RELEASED FROM THE MEDICAL FACILITY WITH NO TREATMENT REQUIRED AT 11:05 PM.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DUFFY EXON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED HE HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY MR. HOLIHAN, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, COLTON YARD, AND ADVISED OF AN ODOR IN THE AREA OF A BUTYL ACELATE TANKCAR. THE TANKCAR, DBUX 260199, WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 314 OF THE DEPARTURE AREA.  MR. HOLIHAN ADVISED NO ACTUAL LEAK HAD BEEN REPORTED, HOWEVER, A CARMAN HAD REPORTED AN ODOR OF "FINGER NAIL POLISH REMOVER" IN THE AREA. MR. HOLIHAN ADVISED THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT REPORT THIS AS AN EXPOSURE AND DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ATTENTION. ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 06:32 AM MGR. BAVIER REPORTED THE LEAKING TANKCAR WAS UTLX 902468, A LOAD OF METHYL METHACRYLATE. THE LEAK WAS DESCRIBED AS A DRIP FROM THE TOP RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE.  NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED AND NO INJURIES REPORTED. THE TANKCAR WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE AN OPEN LIQUID VALVE WITH THE CLOSURE CAP LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE TANKCAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.  NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 02:23 PM, LES LAWSON, MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, ADVISED THAT THE CARMAN WHO ORIGINALLY REPORTED THE ODOR IN THE YARD CLAIMED TO BE SHORT OF BREATH AND LIGHT HEADED APPROXIMATELY 90 MINUTES AFTER THE ORIGINAL INCIDENT WAS REPORTED.  MR. LAWSON STATED THE EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED TO EMPIRE OCCUPATIONAL HEALTH CLINIC FOR EVALUATION AND RELEASED WITH NO INJURIES REPORTED.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, LEO MARQUEZ, DISCOVERED A VAPOR ODOR COMING FROM THE AREA OF FOUR TANKCARS ENTRAINED TOGETHER ON THE MEPHN 21 IN THE WEST TUCUMCARI SIDING.  ALL WERE PLACARDED EMPTIES LAST CONTAINING METHYL TERT BUTYL ETHER. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TANKCAR GETX 3108 HAD FOUR LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS THAT CAUSED A VAPOR RELEASE.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE ALL TIGHTENED 2 ½ TURNS. TWO OTHER TANKCARS WERE NOTED TO HAVE EXCEPTIONS. BUT NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT GATX 80507 HAD TWO MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE AND EACH WAS TIGHTENED ONE TURN. TANKCAR UTLX48764 HAD FOUR LIQUID VALVE BOLTS LOOSE, EACH OF WHICH WAS TIGHTENED ½ TURN.

RAUL MEZA, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT, REPORTED CHARLIE GONZALES, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED A FOUL ODOR NEAR TRACK 204. MR. MEZA INSPECTED TANKCAR ECUX 155087, AND FOUND A LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLT. SAHM MEZA TIGHTENED THE BOLT AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

JAMES SMITH, YARD MASTER, REPORTED MICHAEL JOSEPH CONDUCTOR, ENTERED THE YARD AT BEAUMONT, WALKING PAST TRAIN QDYNL 29, WAS EXPOSED TO ANHYDROUS, AMMONIA.  TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED, AND RESPONDED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  AT 06:10 AM, ALLEN, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, ADVISED THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE AND HAD NARROWED THE POSSIBLE RELEASE DOWN TO THREE TANKCARS. REGIONAL MANAGER O'BRIEN DETERMINED THAT TANKCAR PLMX 2583 WAS LEAKING AS A RESULT OF MISALIGNED O-RING IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVISE.  MR. O'BRIEN REPOSITIONED THE O-RING AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION, INC. DRIVER, DUANE DEWITT LOADED 6 DRUMS OF WASTE AT SEVERN TRENT LABORATORIES IN ARVADA, CO.  HE LOAD LOCKED THE DRUMS AND SECURED THE PALLET JACK WITH BUNGEE STRAPS.  ENROUTE TO THE BUREAU OF LAND MANAGEMENT LOCATED WITHIN DENVER FEDERAL CENTER, DENVER, CO THE STRAPS CAME LOOSE, CAUSING THE PALLET JACK TO ROLL INTO ONE OF THE DRUMS LOADED AT SEVERN TRENT LABORATORIES.  IT MADE A SMALL HOLE, ALLOWING 2 TO 3 GALLONS OF ACETONE CHLOROFORM TO LEAK OUT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN SECURITY AT THE DENVER FEDERAL CENTER CHECKED THE TRAILER BEFORE ENTRY INTO THE FACILITY WAS ALLOWED, THEY DISCOVERED THE LEAK.  THEY CLOSED THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER AND SECURED THE AREA.  THEY CALLED THE LAKEWOOD, JEFFERSON COUNTY, AND ADAMS COUNTY POLICE DEPT. AND FIRE DEPTS AND HAZMAT TEAMS. THEY MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED WHAT WAS LEAKING.  THEY OVER PACKED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN 85 GAL OVER PACK.  SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION CALLED RMCAT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND DECONTAMINATE AS NEEDED.  THIS TRAILER WILL BE INSTALLED WITH AN E-TRACK IMMEDIATELY.  E-TRACK LOCKS AND STRAPS AND TRAINING IN THE USE OF THESE WILL BE SUPPLIED TO ALL DRIVERS MAKING THESE PICKUPS IN THE COLORADO AREA.  E-TRACK IS A METAL STRIP INSTALLED HORIZONTALLY ALONG THE INSIDE WALLS OF THE TRAILER, FOR THE E-TRACK LOCKS AND STRAPS TO BE HOOKED INTO TO SECURE THE PALLET JACK FROM MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION.

PTI OWNER OPERATOR DRIVER, MIKE MAZE, WAS BEING LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT AK STEEL IN MIDDLETOWN, OHIO (SHIPPER) ON AUGUST 22, 2003 TO BE DELIVERED TO UNIVAR USA, INC IN CINCINNATI, OH (CONSIGNEE). AT 8:30 AM LOCAL TIME, THE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD NOISE AND SAW A CRACK IN THE CARGO TANK TRAILER AT THE FRONT HEAD ALONG A WELD SEAM AT THE 11 O'CLOCK POSITION. THE DRIVER AND AK STEEL LOADER STOPPED THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE DRIVER BACKED UP THE UNIT AND ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD.  THE PRODUCT REFRIGERATED IN THE TRANSPORT TRAILER AND UNLOADING WAS STOPPED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED IN ADDITION TO AK STEEL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS.  AREA WAS EVACUATED, 2 PEOPLE TREATED AT THE SITE AND 1 PERSON TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR INHALATION PROBLEMS.  NO SERIOUS INJURIES.  CARGO TANK WAS PUMPED OFF AND INCIDENT ENDED AT 2:30 PM, SUNDAY, AUGUST 24.  THE TRAILER WAS HAULED TO MIDWEST TANK WORKS IN VINCENNES, IN.  THE NTSB, FEDERAL DOT AND OHIO DOT WENT TO THE TANK SHOP, INSPECTED THE TRAILER, TOOK METAL SAMPLES AROUND THE CRACK AND INTERVIEWED THE DRIVER. ROOT CAUSE: CAUSE OF THE CARGO TANK FAILURE WAS LOADING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CONTAINING LESS THAN 0.2% WATER IN A QT (QUENCHED AND TEMPERED STEEL) CARGO TANK.  PREVENTATIVE ACTION: PTI SAFETY DEPARTMENT REVIEWED ALL ANHYDROUS CUSTOMERS' BILLS OF LADING TO ENSURE THAT 0.2% WATER CONTENT IS MARKED ON THE BOLS.  PTI WILL NO LONGER LOAD AT AK STEEL UNLESS PTI ACQUIRES A NQT TRAILER OR AK STEEL CERTIFIES 0.2% WATER CONTENT AND DOCUMENTS THIS ON THEIR BOL.  DRIVER RETRAINED ON THE REQUIREMENTS OF 49 CFR 173.315, NOTE 14.

column168: FILE: 3297 D, SHIPPER: MID-WEST INDUSTRIAL CHEMICAL CO, AWB#: DST 10108142651 BTV.  REVISED REPORT 11/14/03.  AMEDMENTS TO THIS REPORT INCLUDE THE MODE OF TRANSPORTATION AND DATE AND TIME OF INCIDENT.  ON 08/20/03 AT 1517 A LIQUID SPILL WITH A GLUE ODOR WAS REPORTED IN THE SORT AREA OF OUR BTV (OUTBASE STATION) SORTING FACILITY LOCATED AT AIRBORNE EXPRESS, 391 BOYER CIRCLE, WILLISTON, VT 06495.  AT THE TIME OF THE CALL, THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PLACED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE AFFECTED AREA HAD BEEN CLEANED.  WE SENT A SALVAGE DRUM TO RECOVER THIS SHIPMENT SO WE COULD COMPLETE THE NECESSARY INVESTIGATION AND 5800.1 REPORT. ONCE WE RECEIVED THE DRUMMED SHIPMENT PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN CAROLYN FRYE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR BRUCE SHILTZ DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND STARTED THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX INSIDE THE DRUM TO CONTAIN 1 X 4 OF "ADHESIVES, 3, UN 1133, PG II" IN A METAL CAN WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THE CLOSURE ON THIS CAN WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE CLOSURE ON THIS CAN CAME LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 4 L. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND HAD THE PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN THE TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR AT THE BTV STATION.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THE CONTACT PERSON AT THE BTV STATION IS JONNEAN WARNER/ AD COORD AND SHE CAN BE REACHED AT 802-882-4018.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED CONTAINER CAXU 642839 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS AT WHITE 409, ICTF. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SCENE AND THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMERS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED.  THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE LADING OF FIVE GALLON PAILS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD. SEVERAL PAILS WERE OBSERVED CRUSHED FROM SHIFTING OFF OF THE PALLET AND TOPPLING.  THERE WERE VOIDS BETWEEN THE TWO REAR FLOOR LOADED PALLETS.  THE PAILS WERE STRETCH WRAPPED ON THE PALLETS, BUT NOT TO THE PALLETS.  AS THERE WAS NO FILLER IN THE VOID SPACE, THE PAILS MOVED OFF OF ONE SIDE OF THE PALLETS AND BEGAN TO TOPPLE, PLACING AN UNEVEN WEIGHT ON THE LOWER PAILS, CAUSING THEM TO BE CRUSHED.  WHILE REMOVING THE BACK HALF OF THE LADING, LOCATED NINE CRUSHED PAILS, WHICH LOST APPROXIMATELY 45 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  ONE ADDITIONAL PAIL WAS FOUND LEAKING, AND ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGE TO WHERE IT WAS DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  THE LEAKING PAIL WAS PLACE INTO A SALVAGE DRUM WITH THE DAMAGED PAIL FOR SECUREMENT.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER THEN MOVED TO A LOCAL WAREHOUSE FOR RECOOPING.
